Parliament did not ratify the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament has refused, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the proposed annulment of the paragraph on the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs rejected at second reading the proposed amendment to reduce penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for concluding an a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court must rule on the appeal of the sentenced in December.
Tymosenko called the ruling a political revenge of the regime and provoked a process of suspicions of bias from the court to the west as well.
The proposal to overturn paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 Members of Parliament.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
