The feeding of an obese child: does not take breakfast and takes cold cuts for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, 9% of schoolchildren will be overweight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This shows again how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the patterns that surround it are.
On the tables of obese children, for example, charcuterie is found 50% more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to survey conducted with awareness-raising action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of big kids, sports is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today - only 15% answered that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic participated.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever company.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from the sixth to the third grade have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of children who are overweight, even obese, is the lack of proper diet and not enough physical exercise.
“Only half of the children surveyed say eating breakfast five times a day – in case – lunch – tasting – dinner, which is a basic principle of a good diet,” says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and cold meats for dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes a few basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students’ families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone has breakfast alone.
And the worst that's been reported is that one-tenth of the population doesn't have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in the families of obese children, unhealthy fries are more often consumed.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children surveyed exercise regularly but for parents this is half, only 15%.
Prepare Your Food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food from possibilities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
“The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal, in terms of healthy eating.”
Among their favorite dishes are lots of cakes, meats and sweets.
“The most alarming is notably a high preference for sweet lemonades,” the survey results indicate.
For lunch it was the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
The children did not want starches at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Heading to Health
The survey also showed that children are willing to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a review of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the "Obesity is not a coincidence" awareness session, there was a determined willingness to move towards a healthy diet," the survey results indicate.
The most notable was for example with regard to sweet lemonades as children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often ticked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as their main course and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread flour pellets or potatoes).
