IBM History: From slices of cheese to flights into the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it initially had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80s of the tenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 presided over the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the firm’s founder – the company’s identity and culture have so far been based on Watson’s ideas.
Watson ran the Kusqu firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson’s leadership, revenue increased to $9 million and the company began expanding in all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable to the firm that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM people and computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos – on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time under the name IBM 5150 came to market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to take care of consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has been successful at IBM over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
In terms of commerce IBM recently developed a "Smarter Commerce" platform that helps marketers manage the entire trading cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in our territory.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also Brno’s strategic outsourcing center.
The Central for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team that deals with speech recognition.
