How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a westward inclination and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovakian citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but you had to queue up all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn’t won yet.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who couldn't travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs were buying and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989, Czech travel has undergone a major revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak, Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million vacation days in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The removal of visas in the 90s of the last century in the western neighbouring countries has caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by air to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical trait of a Czech trip at that time was to take with you your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary increased which caused around the year 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel travel agencies have begun since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter connections that through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 1990s the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world apart from the US, which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008 the EU removed visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully fit into the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time ever again in history spent more than 15,000 kronor per person for holidays abroad including ancillary charges.
