The most beautiful swimming pools in Europe
A jump in the blue
By Julia Stanek
UFO-optic pools, beautiful pools of Budapest: Who travels through Europe can live his blue miracle - and after having toured the city or taking a long walk - can let his tired legs rest in soda baths.
A book shows in which swimming pool one can experience the most well-being.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip for the last 18 months, there is one thing that should not be missing in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying on her back in the water, she looked at the artistically arranged domes, and swam against the Putten marbles that were waiting for her on the other side of the pool and did not fail to admire the meticulously restored Art Nouveau of these converted pools.
If an indoor pool pleased her, she immediately noted in her notebook all the interesting details about the type of construction and the history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools have been surveyed in this way by architectural historian Meder and she presented them in her already published book: "Badefreiheiten (Bathing Jewels). The municipal indoor swimming pools of München, the historic bathing palaces in the black forest, "hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
She has conducted her "travels to the most exceptional baths in Central Europe" in 13 countries. Besides Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she has visited places in Italy, France, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland and a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia respectively.
The 46-year-old German is a true enthusiast of bathing culture.
Meder explains that she doesn’t have much interest in the sport but he feels attracted to the water in a totally different way.
It's annoying that swimmers should just look at blue tiles and settle for the stench of bleach while joggers breathe in the scent of bewitching spruce forests or can hear the buzz of happy park birds.
"I once wondered why the pools should always be so ugly," said the Viennese.
"So I started a collection of beautiful baths."
The surface of the water reinforces the architecture doubly
A swim in a swimming pool and volatile sauna oils - wellness factor in the swimming rooms are huge because all the senses are awake, according to Meder.
And if the builders had given themselves a little more trouble, the swimming rooms could be a real treat for the eyes: "Instead of a floor you have a surface of water in the swimming rooms."
"It's transparent on one side, but it reflects the beauty of the whole building on the other side."
All surfaces are optically presented in a double way: high vaults, multicolored tiles, stepping stones.
The small image volume "Badefreiheitn" makes a 190-page interesting report on the history of architecture and culture on the oasis of historical well-being - it certainly makes you want to take a leap into the blue.
The collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
Next to the splendid wellness baths such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found water containing nitrate in a natural cave in the karst (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a bath of baths whose pools are filled with water containing alkali and (Városi Termálfürdö in a sezberían find).
On the other hand, the heated outdoor pools of Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views. While you have the whole city in your eyes from one roof of the Zurich bath, you can admire the snowy Arlberg from an outdoor pool of St. Anton: The Turkish bath is equipped with a window from which you can see the animation on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits swimmers in Längenfeld: The Aqua Dome Ötztal looks like a UFO just landed on the Alps.
In winter, steam rises from the three open plateaus, while in the background rises the Ötztal mountains towards the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
The smell of bleach does not emanate from all the pools in the Meder collection.
Many thermal baths emanate a smell of sulfur, the Árpád-spa in the Hungarian Bekescsaba emanates a strong smell of oil, which is hard to believe, to be in a healthy spa.
The odor comes from the therapeutic alkaline waters containing carbon hydrogen that is almost black and its sludge sticks to your skin as soon as you let yourself slip into the pool – a special spa experience.
During her quest for beautiful swimming pools, Iris Meder also suffered disappointments: When she wanted to visit Bad Luhatschowitz, a free outdoor pool in Czechoslovakia, she found herself in front of a barricaded plot of land.
The bath designed by the architect Dushan Jurkovic in 1902 was in the meantime closed.
Taking a look through the window of the Art Nouveau building in red-white-yellow, she observed the blossoming of weeds between the tiles.
She observed the opposite effect in a charming pool in the Black Forest: Bad Wildbad’s thermal bath palace.
This building has already survived three phases; you can discover not only neo-Roman elements that have come out since its design in 1844 but also a Moorish room in Alhambra style that was added to it in 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the thermal palace has remained the favourite bath of pool expert Iris Meder - and not only because it is native to Schwarzwald.
“It’s already a great achievement to merge such different building styles into such a great unit,” says Meder.
With such a palace, diving in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor issue.
