21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion that moved
Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and acts as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about modern post-war architecture, its clear shapes, its glass sheds, its bright and bold looks and its new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl schwanzer for the world exhibition in Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight and suspended steel and glass construction.
Construction is considered to be an important step in contemporary architecture to this day.
He made the architects so famous that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian world exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at Vienna’s South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the artworks, so not a good environment.
However it was used for so long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has become increasingly dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name "Maison du 21ème siècle" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every respect.
The new start was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career in her youth as an art skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, she has particularly carried out the work of transformation with politicians and monumental protection, she has obtained public funds and sponsorship.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba, whose foundation bears the same name, have been exhibited, a café and a bookstore are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict monitoring, small budget
Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had sensibly transformed and expanded Joseph Olbracht's secession and he had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of his move to Vienna and his change of use.
In the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "a gulf of energy," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, fiberglass-reinforced insulating glass was installed and the roof was replaced by a special safety glass.
The thermal bridge beams have been reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a panel of dimmed light between the house and the road ensures lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - this is almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remained, the house is painted in a shade of red-brown rust protection.
And the movie theater is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and inexpensive had to be found, and that also please the monuments protection office," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to raw soil in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
It would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz said recently, a typical "Drop-in-the-City" story.
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a chance shot of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands precisely the newly planned "central station district" with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck may happen: the 21st century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city in order to get a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
