The personal mass slaughter
Peter Englund's new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a long list of characters that cling to your heart.
A tip to get started: tear this page down carefully and make it your bookmark.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this novel by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the haze of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately describes as "a work of anti-history."
It has some well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors or discussions about strategies and materials.
It’s not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a “book describing what it might look like.”
“Beauty and sorrow” summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulancemen and vendors.
Some will become heroes.
Some will lose limbs, go crazy, or lose their lives.
Their lives are wavering here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are lit.
Peter Englund's book deviates from traditional history books.
It brings a denial to the idea that World War I can only be summed up by the terrible trench war on the Western front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks the rope.
When gunshots sound in the distance, and you’re a home mom, do you stay or run away?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “the lack of facts has been compounded by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors.”
"Beauty and sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly taken from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
Versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most of them deal with deprivation and the ability to get away with it.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He is currently working on alternative food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from cooked rice crushed into sheep's fat (and finished with a fake wood bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
He states that "837 permitted substitute meats are registered in sausage production. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
Some stories deal with honor and courage.
An American recognizes his own drive toward savagery and declares of war: "You feel that after all this is what men were meant for, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whisky by hand, reading a newspaper or a best-seller, and rather than pretending that such a varnish is synonymous with civilization, and that there is no beard behind it.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is very likely to die, and that no one will notice or pay attention to him.
“When you’re resigned to sacrifice, you hope to have an audience,” he writes.
It is, unfortunately, rather like “a convicted man strangled in secret.”
