7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Lost Interview at the Movies This Week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most revealing in a recently found Steve Jobs interview that will air this week as the first part of a film in major markets, is how much this creative mind had understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer; he identified himself as a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a flowchart enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease, leaving them to think that a brilliant idea does 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates d'idea from d'manuel.
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which traces the birth of the computer, and he sat down for over an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
By that time, Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple for about 10 years, already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aiming for a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the major copies have disappeared in the transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs that a complete video was found in the director's garage.
This video, slightly raised, is the basis of the 68-minute film called Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be released in cinemas next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs seems here surprisingly excited to expose technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs weighs his thoughts clearly, in order to provide a precise answer.
There are also moments when Steve Jobs’s perfectionism resurfaces, when he seems eager to hear Cringely’s questions, giving him elbowsticks to speed him up and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the Pixar, iPod or iPhone era, Steve Jobs evaluates what he sees as good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision for the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read Steve Jobs’ posthumous career reviews, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then implements them.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences from Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
“During all these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers are constantly the same: ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to detail his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" assessed at the nose and then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed accurate calculation of business costs.
On the Opportunity to Play a Tour to the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack into phone networks and make long-distance free calls.
The device has been the subject of many previous writings, but Steve Jobs’ euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We wrapped the ball in different things a half-dozen times and you were screaming in the public phone and it would happen to you a minute later on the public phone next door,” Jobs laughed.
“We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn't both know much, but we were able to invent a little thing that could control great things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without that.
Steve Jobs goes on to recount a wonderful tour that he and Wozniak have worked out: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night posing as Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices leave insanely laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett’s approach):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he looks for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP's employees to visit the company's Palo Alto research labs, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed."
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube, and I fell in love with him.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On Improvisation of Innovation:
Several times in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products at a glance.
Early in his career, as he settled down to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asked him to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 credit days, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember some big arguments... I was yelling at by pretending it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse we could make for $15 that was incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are running low:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
"Suppose you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, what after?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [these are these types of people] who end up leading businesses and product-focused staff are pushed away from decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who can’t imagine designing a good product versus a bad product – the manual labor required.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been 10 times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They wrestled defeat from victory.
On Innovation as an Artistic Form:
“A huge piece of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are some compromises to be made... Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories, too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made out of personal taste, trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists fly.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
This is partly what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
Scalia and Thomas dine with health law opponents as court meets
The day the Supreme Court meets in camera to examine the issue of political discord, namely whether opposition to President Obama’s health law will be heard, two of his judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were spotted at a law firm-sponsored dinner that will defend the case in the high court.
The event took place last Thursday, when the nine judges gathered for a conference to discuss petitions for review.
One of the cases involved a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the ambitious health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying point for conservative activists nationwide.
The judges agreed to hear the complaint, in fact, a monumental argument of 5:30 a.m. is expected next March, and the result will likely be likely to favor the destabilization of the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court decision is rendered.
The lawyer who will stand before the court and argue about rejecting the law will likely be Paul Clement, who served as solicitor general of the United States during the George W. Bush administration.
Clément’s law firm, PLLC Bancroft, was one of two dozen firms that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a long-standing group dedicated to defending conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another promoter was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, which presents a huge financial stake in the outcome of the lawsuit.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel a few hours after the court conference on the case.
There was, among others, Mitch McConnell, a top Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the health law.
Star guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
This is not new: both judges have been present at the events of the Federalist Society for years.
And there is nothing that goes against the rules of ethics.
In fact, judges are exempt from the code of conduct that governs the actions of federal judges.
If they were, they would probably argue with the Canon 4C code, which states: “A judge may attend fundraisers from law-related organizations and others although the judge may not be an intervenor, guest of honor, or appear on the program of such an event.”
Nevertheless, the mere presence of Scalia and Thomas near two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a massive financial interest, was enough to alarm government ethics activists.
“This violation of ethics and superb indifference to the code contradicts the statements of several judges that the court respects the same rules applicable to all other federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
“Judges were drinking and dining and at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending in court.”
Their presence and participation in the fundraising of this event dispels any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little regard for critics saying they too easily mix court affairs with the agenda of groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas’ wife, Ginni, is a high-profile conservative activist.
Moreover, the Conservatives claim that it is Judge Elena Kagan who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was solicitor general of the Obama administration when the first objections to the law were brought to the level of the court of first instance.
Her critics pushed for Kagan to refuse to hear the case, saying she had invested too much in the defense of the law to be impartial.
Kagan gave no indication that she would.
