BASD urges Asia to help the eurozone
The Asian Development Bank has asked India and China to prepare to help the eurozone emerge from the sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term decline that would impede the development of the Asian economy.
Rajat Nag, the director general of the Manila-based BASD, said the world’s two fastest-growing economic powers needed to “do everything in their power” to accelerate the recovery of the currency zone through the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements.
He advised the BRICs (Brazil, Russia, India, China) not to look at Europe’s difficulties with an “indifferent eye” and pointed out that Asian financial support alongside Europe’s leaders and resources would help prevent a long-term collapse of the global economy.
“We are all together in this crisis.”
“Therefore anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is helpful,” he told the Financial Times during an interview during the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
“Asia can be protected to a certain extent, but it is not safe.”
“So if China and India can help, there’s nothing to stop them.”
In recent months, the eurozone has been seriously shaken by a sovereign debt crisis.
Recently, the cost of Italian borrowing has skyrocketed dangerously and the Prime Ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The booming sovereign debt crisis in Europe has raised fears that the global economy will go into recession, and has prompted calls from major emerging economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Nag predicted that the IMF would channel any Asian aid, but he also said that this bilateral assistance – such as buying the bonds of the U.S. financial rescue fund, the European Financial Stability Fund – offered greater negotiating power to Europe’s Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, India's trade and industry minister, said that "India will do everything it can" to help the euro zone as its own economy now suffers from a decline in exports and a slowdown in foreign capital inflows.
“Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and uneasy,” he said.
“We have monumental challenges to meet and we need to maintain a high level of growth.”
“It’s not a choice, it’s an imperative, because where would we find work for the tens of millions of our young men and women?”
Others argue that developing economies such as India should not help rich Europeans as they face their own major economic challenges.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the United States, said it would be politically very difficult to get the 1.2 billion Indians, at least 800,000 of whom live on $2 a day or less, to accept aid to Europe.
“One day, they will discover that the Greeks are retiring at 50 and going on vacation in the sun and they will have a hard time swallowing it,” he said.
Lee Howell, the president of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India’s reserves should be used to keep many well-paid Greek officials in poorly managed jobs that generate losses, such as in the rail sector.
Nag said the eurozone crisis was likely to cause “significant repercussions” across Asia.
BASD’s forecast for economic growth of 7.5% in Asia in 2011/2012 now faces “loss risks” due to the European threat.
He noted that vulnerable emerging markets needed to develop “relief plans” to protect themselves from economic downturn and significant capital leaks.
Pentagon warns of potential defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta raised pressure on Congress on Monday, warning that impending automatic budget cuts would undermine national security, triggering a financial chain reaction from Pentagon corridors to Afghanistan’s battlefields, to civilian rallies.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts for the next decade, but now fears that an additional $600 or more in cuts is imminent if Congress fails to agree on spending.
“The impacts of these cuts would be devastating for the ministry,” Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said Congress’ failure to reach a budget deal resulting in what is called sequestration would result in 23% cuts as well as the freezing of many new projects.
“Such a significant reduction, applied indiscriminately, would render most of our ships and construction projects unenforceable – you can’t buy three-quarters of a ship or a ship – and seriously undermine other modernization efforts,” Panetta wrote.
“We would also be forced to separate from a number of our civilian personnel and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we almost certainly should send civilians on leave without pay in order to achieve the goal.”
“These changes would undermine the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our readiness.”
The reductions would eventually affect the fighting troops, Panetta continues.
“Although wartime funding of foreign contingency operations accounts is not directly affected by sequestration, war efforts would be negatively affected by severe disruptions in core budgets,” Panetta said.
“Contracting personnel would be reduced, resulting in delays in contracts and oversight of contracts that support the war.”
“Salary management staff would be reduced, leading to delays in payment to war suppliers, and legal and political support would be disrupted.”
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details on the potential impact of automatic compressions on the Department of Defense.
“The consequence of a sequestration on the Department of Defense would trigger a rapid decline of the United States as the undisputed world leader of military power.”
“We are fiercely opposed to this draconian action,” the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon during the publication of Panetta’s letter.
“It’s not a consequence we can live with, and it’s certainly not the one we should be imposing on ourselves.”
“Sequestration is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen.”
Whether Panetta’s letter and recent senators’ warnings increase pressure for a budget compromise or a call to exempt the Pentagon from cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly virulent about possible cuts, even though he himself has come to the top of the Pentagon, accumulating years of budget expertise in Congress and the White House and knowing he was facing tough choices.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a dark picture of what might happen - a military with a shell, but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a bullet-free brigade."
"It's a fighter jet, with not enough trained pilots."
“It’s a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that don’t have enough trained soldiers capable of accomplishing the mission,” Panetta said.
“It’s a depressed force, poorly prepared and unable to cope with potential adversaries.”
"Indeed, it invites aggression."
In an addendum to her letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifically stated how further reductions could “generate significant operational risks: time to respond to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limitations on our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and unacceptable risk assumed in future combat operations.”
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could move to the cutting edge, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
This list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a new planned bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship, and the new field vehicle, which would replace the Army and Navy Humvee.
Putting an end to the development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its proponents say it is a critical step in improving and responding to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines shows how pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies have destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has gone dumb by quickly issuing contradictory denials with irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to covering an extramarital liaison.
And then, none of those who have lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton sparked by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legion.
There have been instances where teachers have given test responses to students in order to get a good look at their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie to each other three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to shout: "I had you," deception detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades from prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, particularly in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don’t stutter, blush or stir at all times.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can uncover the truth by examining the statement structure, facial micro-expressions, question formation, and response time.
I’ve spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it’s clear that deception detection is a modern skill that’s easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are skilled at reading others well, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more lies "centered" while women tell more lies "centered" - usually to protect someone's feelings - than married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "setting the benchmark data".
This helps provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe your subject’s posture, laughter, vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally stirs their feet permanently so as not to throw unfair accusations when you see them stir their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for indications of verbal and nonverbal deceptive behaviors.
Think of these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the upper body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly, or present a “post-interview” relief – an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult issues have passed.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to seek to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to your subject’s vocabulary.
The famous Scott Peterson skidded using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use distant language: "I haven't had sex with this woman...Miss Lewinsky" or completely repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wooden tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing the skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
