February’s low temperatures, aside from causing losses of trillions for the agricultural sector, limited the state’s economic opportunities for growth, caused a 3.6 percent contraction in overall economic activity in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic 31.16 percent decline in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report of jelly assignments issued by the Mexican Council of Sustainable Rural Development, there were damages of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the rest 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and chick peas.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, which increased the unemployment rate of the state during the first three quarters of the year, because from January to March 55 thousand 053 signooens were unemployed, with a rate of 18 per cent in the second half of the year.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly depending on the actions carried out by public policy.
“What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars in an illicit way it is not easy for them to work to earn them, to invest them and to use them in something,” he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
“The number of people leaving the state to work abroad in the United States has been restricted, first because of entry difficulties and second because on entering they already have a lot of difficulty finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which makes unemployment rise,” he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the labor market in Signoen is aggravated considering the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in this state work there without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Aside from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the state's lag is low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to records from the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly earnings of the workers from Signoen was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which stands at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the State FDI reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, representing a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the Government of the State has a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the State Government requested in July at the public congress the approval of a loan of 3 trillion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was of 2,600 trillion pesos and until November the government did not see any profit in the sector.
Reactions
For the representatives of the employers' sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés' Government demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the State Government.
"The performance of the Sinaloa economy during this year was really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we had to align the effort of all and especially the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events like the frosts at the beginning of the year have held back the state’s economy and restricted its yield and growth.
“The low economic flow is produced by several events, among which frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of e flow in trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close well below the expectations we had,” he says.
Redefining the Vocation
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa, we want to channel the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important to detonate the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he says.
Much to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in the way public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have worked a lot and the Government is aware that there is still a lot to do," he says.
