Court Validates ‘Analog Cutting’ in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called “analog cut” from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been met.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree that details the actions to be taken to achieve the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was rejected for not having reached the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as unconstitutional, due to the fact that radio and television regulations are an assignment reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the reservation of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions provided by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of ministers also resolved to dismiss the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister-President said that he disagreed with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also do not consider that doing so would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, whose constitutional mandate is the direction of the state.
Substitution of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this translates into better radio spectrum exploitation, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing change, he argued, would be postponing the benefits of digitalization that involves a public-interest decision that does not only have a technical dimension, “because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, encompasses a group of powers that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the State Executive".
He recalled that many countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, has in any way invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative, he assured.
The possibility of a "vote-by-vote" count in Michoacán is analyzed
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of the "vote-by-vote" count is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 minutes.
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with federal reform in electoral matters.
It will be remembered that Michoacán did not approve either his Political Constitution or his State Electoral Code or his Electoral Justice Act, at the same time that the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral process to come into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel had omitted its publication of the Off-State Law with the deadlines laid down by the Off-State Law.
On the same November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and described as "invalid and illegal" the state's proxy vote for constitutional reforms, because it has no right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there are no minutes of votes and counts in the record of the ballot box is not found in the president of the ballot box; or there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the votes received in all ballot boxes of the election may be achieved when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate who is supposed to have won the respective election and the candidate who obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the representative of the party and/or the co-sponsor.
The total count of the vote can also be achieved if at the end of the common count it turns out that the difference between the supposed winning candidate and that of the second place is equal to or less than a percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the representative of the political party from which the candidate came second, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
