The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the brink of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire Eurozone.
A presidential palace statement said Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he can form the government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed of technocrats in its majority, even if it is not clear when the new executive will take over.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," he said.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "frame is now well laid out," he added.
Monti has completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy is battling a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a harsh austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability has placed the yield on Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland have had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, the leader of Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We have said that we will greatly support this government."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency.
Monti’s chances for success were greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, which the crisis forced him to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government needs strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could cause a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers’ groups and youth and women’s organizations.
He will end his meeting tour on Tuesday night.
Monti was named Sunday by Napolitano, who enabled an extremely fast transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the Eurozone.
Monti said his government should persist until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before the elections advance.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist it should only be trained by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
