Quinteto has included the country in his turn to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to perform one of their best shows next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to happen in this country.
That’s what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, of Brazil, last week.
The band is in the South American wing of its two-decade-long celebration tour and will make its only stopover in Central America on Sunday.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., next to the Los Angeles band The X and the Las Robertas nationals.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For its Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will perform in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I’ve only been to Costa Rica once on vacation; it’s such a beautiful country and I think we’ll be able to spend a few days there.
So it makes us excited to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live intensely the previous days.
What is your message to your most devoted followers?
Thank you for staying with us for all these years.
It took us 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to pass until this concert.
Some people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does it add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve offered over the past 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We have offered two gigantic shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that it has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing there.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going to go surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next door to Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we learned it, through the people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you offered huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never been there, we have no restrictions as to what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's the point of this?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can perform more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, which is why it’s very difficult to choose which songs to perform each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t performed in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved those songs and may have forgotten about them.
It makes the show more interesting to us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting to people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us had imagined that we were going to be a big rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it sound like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together excites us a lot.
We love each other and love to create music.
We’re lucky to go to places in the world we’ve always wanted to go.
Things couldn't get better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group of big groups.
We are very friendly with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
This is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is unusual.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it’s much stranger when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honoured to be part of the Seattle Group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw in Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to still be friends with all of them and it’s an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It’s also very strange that a group like yours has been together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that is much longer than many bands normally last.
Firstly, I believe that we are all lucky to be still alive, and secondly, we all care about others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give freedom to everyone to experience.
We have confidence in each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity hasn’t been easy; however, thanks to your success, you’ve been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don’t spend too much time on tour because it’s easy to fall into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
If we don’t forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we have to respect the music and what brought it, without thinking about the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which doesn’t really interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn’t release a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration for the fact that it lasted so little and the most important thing is the fact that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us and when I listen to a song or I see a photo I think about the incredible person that Andy has been and how he made me laugh with music a lot, it was always a pleasure to talk about it.
He was a surprising human being and we miss him.
