Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake and seven other people died
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before the take-off of the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"Elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees within 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations made in the impact zone do not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In research it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact was presented in a structural way.
“The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a slope of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For now, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as quickly as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services assured that at the time of the impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was operating at cruising speed and this happened on a soft ascending ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruising operation at the time of impact," he said.
During the press conference, TBS holder Pérez Jácome listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual Theft:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was performed according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned suitable conditions for take-off, and as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between DF and the State of Mexico, there were layers of low-rise cloudiness.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew sought an area of lower height and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a reduced area:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact took place on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The model of dispersion of the remains of the aircraft makes it possible to assume that the helicopter collided with the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion were detected:
At the site of the disaster there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had had multiple ground contacts.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above the average sea level, the ground had a slope that went from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he possibly disjointed along his journey.
The information provides evidence that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After a thorough search in a wider area than the encircled area around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the presumption that the impact took place under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and youth; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and youth, called the 'Genetics of Obesity of Children and Adolescents' protocol that will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
Investigators are invited to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence is made to minors every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the target of 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation is to know the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires related to food.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of their diseases, to avoid the risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that Saturdays will be applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (seeking to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
“The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there has been a 77 percent increase in obesity for boys and 47 percent for girls; in the case of overweight, there has also been a dramatic increase,” said the IMSS expert.
He said the rationale for finding markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American, 30 percent European and five percent African heredity and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity results in the inability to burn the excess energy that is consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the full evaluation of the children, which makes it possible to detect if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even says that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, and doctors give it in writing to parents, who are told each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - cornmeal pâté wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt from UNAM would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a blend with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the cassis could even be completely eliminated.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Cassava, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for developing asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and therefore, cassis formation.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The QC researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, according to the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, is put a last layer called rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide grip in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be cared for.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and as a result causes cassis.
In the process of formation of a cassis, he says, the first that spoils is rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent formation of cassis.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair cassis easily and without having to use high temperatures.
