“If Bashar had the interest of his country at heart, he should resign, but he should also create the necessary conditions for a new phase of Syrian political life,” the King of Jordan, a neighboring country of Syria, said in an interview with the BBC.
Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoglu said Turkish mediation efforts with the Syrian regime since the beginning of the year had failed.
“Those who are not at peace in the Middle East with their people and cannot satisfy them will leave,” he said, referring to Syria, a neighboring country to which Turkey is taking an increasingly hard line.
The United States, for its part, welcomed a “strengthening of the consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime” following the decisions of the Arab League and the European Union.
“The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League, countries like Turkey are taking on an increasingly harsh tone” in the face of repression in Syria, noted Mark Toner, a spokesman for the State Department.
Meanwhile, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the regime’s forces have died in southern Syria’s Deraa region, the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSDH) said.
Two other civilians were killed "in exchanges of fire and shelling with heavy machine guns in Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, according to the NGO.
At a news conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Mouallem said the country was “going towards the end of the crisis.”
He also reacted strongly to the Arab League's decision to suspend Damascus from its work, which he said was "a dangerous step".
Syria “will not bow,” he added, assuring that “the bold plots against Syria will fail.”
Following its decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is now studying a “civilian protection mechanism” and wishes to send 500 members of Arab human rights organizations, media and military observers to the country.
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppé also said he was in favour of sending UN observers to help protect civilians from the regime’s repression, which he said was entrenched in “paranoia.”
A new extraordinary meeting of the League is scheduled tomorrow in Rabat to take stock of the implementation of the crisis relief plan decided on November 2, including the withdrawal of the armed forces from the cities under protest and the release of the arrested protesters.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov yesterday deemed the Arab League's decision "incorrect", while China urged Syria to implement the crisis relief plan, while refraining from supporting possible sanctions against Damascus.
