A Russian scientist has helped Iran's nuclear program
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, has helped Iran develop a detonator that can be used with a nuclear weapon, an American NGO specializing in atomic risk said on Monday.
The Institute for International Science and Security (ISIS) relies on the recent report of the International Atomic Security Agency (IAEA) and other documents from that UN agency to identify this researcher.
The IAEA said last week it was "seriously concerned" about a "possible military dimension" of Iran's nuclear program.
According to ISIS drawing heavily on IAEA documents, Mr. Danilenko, born in 1934, reportedly worked for three decades starting in the 1960s in a Soviet military nuclear center in Chelyabinsk (Ural), and was involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, he reportedly left the center to establish a company producing "nano-diamonds" in Kiev.
The economic difficulties of his company would have led him to contact the Iranian embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
He then cooperated with the Iranian program from 1996 to 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA referred to "strong indications that Iran's development" of a nuclear detonation system "was aided by the work of a foreign expert, who not only knew this technique well, but who, as a member state informed the Agency, worked for most of his career on this technology within the military nuclear program of his home country."
Anti-Muslim Crimes and Crimes Increased by 50%
Crimes and crimes against Muslims increased by nearly 50 percent from 2009 to 2010, while other racial and religious violence declined slightly or progressed little, according to FBI statistics released Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of violence against Muslims increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, a 49% increase, compared to a 13% increase in violence against Catholics, a 4% decrease in crimes against Jews and a 14% increase in anti-religious crimes.
The total number of “hate crimes” rose very slightly to 6,628 cases, of which 47.3% were motivated by racial differences and 20% by religious differences, according to the FBI.
“After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and offenses increase again,” the human rights organization Human Rights First said, “the increase in anti-Muslim violence is particularly significant.”
“Human Rights First has long stressed that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crime, should be considered a serious human rights violation,” said Paul Legendre, head of the organization.
“The U.S. government can and must do more to address these abuses,” he added, adding that this could lead to improved police reporting on “hate crimes.”
The “hate crime” in U.S. federal law is a legacy of the era of the struggle for civil rights.
This legislation was passed after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence related to race, skin color, religion, origin and now sexual belonging.
