Austria
Inclusion of a "golden rule" in the constitution
Austria’s ruling Social Democratic/Christian Democratic grand coalition government decided on Tuesday to enshrine a budgetary “golden rule” in the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible degradation by Austria’s sovereign rating agencies (triple A).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a council of ministers, while the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the maximum 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were to be lowered by only one notch, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more interest each year,” said Michael Spindelegger, vice chancellor and Christian-Democratic foreign minister.
Austria is responding to a request from the Eurozone summit in Brussels on 26 October: the Heads of State and Government had then called for the inclusion by the end of 2012 of the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts in the constitution or in a law of the same value.
The system adopted by the Austrian government is close to the "German model", with Germany being the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural public deficit will have to decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, from 2017, the federal government’s structural public deficit will not have to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states and municipalities will have to present balanced budgets.
The objective is to move public debt to 2020/21 under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
