Noda threatens new intervention in the foreign exchange market
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that the Japanese authorities would intervene again in the foreign exchange market if the yen were to continue to rise.
"We will intervene as we did last time if we see excessive volatility" in the yen's exchange rate, Noda told the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen was rising not far from the historical levels that prompted Japanese authorities to intervene on October 31.
On that day, Tokyo massively sold yen for dollars in order to lower the value of the Japanese currency that had just set a new record of vigor since 1945 against the greenback.
But the yen has steadily risen since then, boosted by purchases by investors who consider it a “safe haven value” in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar went back under 77 yen on Tuesday and the euro fell below the symbolic bar of 105 yen, close to the levels that triggered the last intervention.
Prior to the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was trading at around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
This surge in the Japanese currency is detrimental to the archipelago's exports because it increases the cost of Made in Japan products and reduces the value of foreign revenues by Japanese firms when they convert them into domestic currency.
"Japan struggles to rebuild" since the March 11 earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Tohoku region, Noda said, fearing that this price increase of the yen would kill the fragile recovery in the egg.
The world’s third-largest economy returned to growth in the third quarter – 1.5% compared to the previous quarter – for the first time in a year, thanks to a rebound in exports and consumption of households hit by the disaster.
But the prime minister said the price of the yen did not reflect "Japan's economic fundamentals."
Finance Minister Jun Azumi called the Bank of Japan (BOJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its monetary policy council on Tuesday, to take all possible steps to weaken the yen.
But the institution’s deputy governor, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BoJ had already taken “appropriate measures,” hinting that no further monetary easing was to be expected on Wednesday.
At its last meeting in late October, the issuing institute increased its purchases of treasury bonds by 5 trillion yen (47 billion euros), increasing the limit on the amounts it devotes to purchases of various financial securities to flood the liquidity market to 55 trillion yen (519 billion euros).
