Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If there is a subject that can not be dealt with from short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influences the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy for an election to be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place that nuclear power holds there.
The debate will be fruitful only if it explores the full range of economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will result in a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless it deprives a huge portion of the world’s population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to overcome the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity permanently, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate disruption, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident did not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case with Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a substitute source, nor with Switzerland, which just wants to build only the latest generation plants.
Conversely, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States, after Fukushima, decided to add a unit to their park by restarting the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, focused on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality contradicts the discourse.
Berlin's choice will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence compounded by the increased use of imported gas, particularly from Russia, a rise in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal power plants.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is worth pondering.
European champion of wind power, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; by virtue of which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Therefore, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not express opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show.
Let us remember that our country’s energy policy has helped to build an industrial chain of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Highly exporting, it drives a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and makes them highly job-creating and non-relocable.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion euros a year of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years when the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, one must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, nor is there any diabolical source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants as well as the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the drama.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident resulted from two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the French and German safety authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that makes it able to withstand such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians eager to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them the clear path to seize leadership in the unavoidable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made the news, with the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23) proclaiming in passing that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
It is because there is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between left and right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising almost 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, fears of invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers were shared on both left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be accorded to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve our “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is perhaps electorally payable; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migrant flows on economic growth.
Restricting immigration anaemia growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are likely to replace national workers, especially low-skilled workers, who are putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national wage earners, with the bulk of their jobs in job-deprived sectors.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the job offer.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will struggle to work in a country that is experiencing a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on nationals' salaries and employment.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in long-term real wages.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenues minus expenditure) of €150,000 to public budgets over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of the term, to go and get the missing growth points "with the teeth".
The teeth in question, when used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be sufficient for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct manner possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was an ease of thinking.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an “instrument of oppression”, as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also, first and foremost, a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true Greek referendum in this respect will have been double revealing: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought of in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a dispersed order.
A white-seing to the absolute European monarch or a leap together in the void of nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want couprets, but a common exercise of right, serene and continuous choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we can no longer stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that bends to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
Together, Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will involve decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except, of course, to lead us to disaster.
After having long fought against this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone now calls for the European economic government.
Or so.
But thinking without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We need to take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The revolution in interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic Europe, a real European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let’s make Europeans.
