The Nord Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe and Russia to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on Tuesday in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte have turned together the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe each year via a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is to be completed by the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same path.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge yard looks like victory.
The project was strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to shut it off from Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But this is at the cost of a weakening of energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has managed, in just five years, to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consuming, and whose deposits are in decline.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically,” François Fillon confirmed when inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles displayed by the Gazprom executives, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of steel sheathed in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at 200 m on average.
To build it, minefields dating from World War II had to be avoided.
“A hundred had to be kidnapped or destroyed, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
There was also a need for more measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project managers gave it up when the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company permanently set up off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have foreseen the welds to have a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, one meter wide in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it delivers accurate information about possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run for 50 years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars on departure, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Joined were the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to the company, for 20 renewable years, all gas transmission capacities.
“Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” Müller said.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay their fees, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specifics of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, of hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, elastic, leaves of a broken white color, as if aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design notebook but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which designates a varnished cotton used to cover benches for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces sold.
We are far from the confidential production of the early years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Difficult to establish a portrait-robot of the buyer, because the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its early days, has almost 100 employees today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city center and has managed to impose her identity.
“We have followed the air of time and this new need to write, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies Moleskine’s development: recently, the brand launched an exhibition “Detour” where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a range of supports.
A success that envied: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th Week for Disabled Employment opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy implemented in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still twice the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the whole population.
Discouraging?
“No,” said Éric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organizes the Disabled Employment Week.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable."
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.”
"But there is still a lot to do."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before they get to work.
They are rather elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that complicate the return to employment, and that "are the node of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, general manager of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit workers with disabilities.
Here are the objective brakes.
It remains the unspoken, evolving mentalities, certainly, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur association for the City indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of workers with disabilities, set in a law of 1987.
The latest known figures, dating from 2008, report a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, rising from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses,” says Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
